<Review>I've had several positive experiences with the dedicated and professional staff at University Tire.  Most recently, I had a full brake service on my 2017 BMW X1.  I initially went in on Saturday and Dante was very forthright with me about the scope of the job.  While the warning message on the car demanded brake pads, he informed that the with BMW vehicles, rotors and sensors must also be replaced so that the alert goes away and the vehicle performs at ideal capacity.  About an hour after performing a no-cost inspection, he confirmed that the full service was required, but that all available shops that sold the parts were not opened and I would have to bring the vehicle in on Monday.  During this exchange, I gave him a ballpark budget.  He went line item by line item ensuring that he priced each one at the lowest bid possible, bringing the overall cost to a point where I could not forsake the offer.  I know I saved at least $300-$400 since the dealership would have been way over what I ended up paying at UT&A.  When I went in on Monday, the staff was ready for me and I was on my way to work.  I received a text message AND followup phone call later that day to inform me that the service was complete.  Close to 5 PM, another call came in to ensure that I was in route and they even offered to wait for me should traffic prove to be an imposition.  I've never had this level of attentive care from an automotive service agency ever!  The payment/hand-off was smooth and drama free and the manager informed me that the service/brakes had a two-year warranty that accompanied the vehicle, no matter the state of residence.  Given how auto service businesses can be insufferable, this delectable experience is one I would repeat in a heartbeat.  I unreservedly recommend this place with gusto and delight. < Text>
My car was suffering from a suspension problem, and needed immediate help. I had it towed to them first thing Tuesday morning, and they checked it out while I was at work. They picked me up at the end of the day and went over the damages item by item with me.
In addition to the suspension and resulting tire damage, they highly recommended that I replace the serpentine belt (cracked with age) and engine valve cover (leaking). I had been to see a mechanic earlier in the month for issues related to both, and they didn't catch that.
What gets them 5 stars? They gave me a complementary car to get home to valley and to work the next day. A big deal for someone who isn't old enough to actually rent a car.
My car was fixed by the end of the next day at the estimate cost. Thanks, University Tire!<//Text>

<rate>5< /rate>< Name>
Robert Fitting Jr<//Name>
< UserId.>
106470701393185206330<//UserId.>
< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>
<GmapID>0x54d1557fa51671bb:0x1165ba80544fb628<//GmapID><Date>1465307589635</Date>< text>
This is one of the very few restaurants open in Eureka after 9pm. The staff was friendly even though we showed up 15 minutes before closing time. We ordered to go instead of opting to dine in, but two parties (4+ each) came in 3-5 minutes after us and they seemed fine letting them dine in, so that may be something normal for them.

Meals are a bit on the pricier side of the scale and seem to average $15/meal. The good was delicious though, you're able to choose vegetables and meats for most of the entrees instead of each item having a fixed list of ingredients. My taco salad was piled high with vegetables and had a tasty base of rice, beans, and small chunks of potato.

TLDR; restaurant staff is totally cool with you showing up near closing time, food is a bit expensive but delicious, and it's open past 9.</text>

<userid>116084454081403104796</userid><Name>Lauren Despres< /Name><time>1523412918185<//time><Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
O.M.G.
So let's just admit it... A lot of restaurants in Humboldt disappoint. Pachangas does NOT. Everything my family or I have ever ordered has been high quality, flavorful, and generously-sized portions.
My personal favorite is the sampler (pro-tip: add mushrooms to the quesodilla) because you get a little bit of everything. The cheese sauce that comes with it is absolutely divine.
No matter how full the restaurant gets I have never waited long for my food. The chips and guacamole are ALWAYS fresh, which I am very picky about.
Anyways, I can't say enough good things about this place. Family feel, impecably clean, and reasonably priced. The best!< /Text>

< Text>
REALLY great food! We had fun sampling beers we would normally never buy, but the wait to get somebody to acknowledge our need for a box was sad. The even longer wait to receive the check was even worse. They removed our plates. They removed the beer samples. My husband left the table to have his after dinner cigarette and then waited in the car before our server FINALLY brought the check. Then the wait for him to pick it up was excruciating. My husband finally had to come back to find out if anything was wrong. In the time it's taken us to be checked out, my review has gone from 5 stars to 3 stars, and I'm still waiting.</Text>

Breck Beatie (IRonin)</user_name>
<time>1558563510861<//time>< rating>
5</rating>
< review>
I have been coming here for years. Revisiting the review. Just came for beer today. Still have to say this is some of my favorite beer in the county. I would rather drink a Screaming Giant (the house double IPA) than most any beer I can think of. The staff are really friendly. The atmosphere is laid back and welcoming. I love this Brew pub. The menu is still somewhat limited, but there are some excellent options available. Bumping it up to 5 stars.

Really delicious beer, friendly service, pretty darn good food.

Not the most elaborate menu, but tasty. The butchers platter has some really good choices, though I  miss the smoked tri tip.

Good selection of beers and they have wine available so my wife (serious non beer drinker) can come and have a nice time. They have games available including a set of dominoes. Nice way to while away a few hours on a Sunday afternoon.

Clientele a lot less annoying than at certain other overly trendy brew pubs.</review>

< text>
We went to Firestone on May 15th 2021. They have redone the patio area in the front. Lots of open area seating covered with a partially shaded pergola. It's a really nice area now outside to enjoy the valley weather. This location has switched over to the "ontap" ordering system. We really liked this system. You essentially use your phone to place orders for food, drinks, etc. This is nice because you can queue up your drinks instead of having to wait for the waitress/waiter to come by and check in on you.

The staff was friendly, quick to bring out the drinks and the food was delicious. The crispy chicken sandwich is my favorite. Sweet with a little kick! Goes great with the Double Mind Haze IPA!

This was a great spot and we are so glad we picked this location for the weekend to enjoy getting out of the house. If you enjoy great craft beer and wine, you won't be disappointed! Highly recommended.<//text>

Incredible. Well worth the 45min drive from down town Santa Barbara. Awesome aging room (so it appears)that you can walk in with all kinds of wooden barrels. Huge to small, a few clay containers and regular sized barrels. Quite a sight. Nice little gift shop and all kinds of hard to find beers. Had some great aged and regular flavored beers. The food was very good. Chefs special burger. No complaints. Great atmosphere. Very creative seating in the restaurant section. Go sip your beer in the gift shop. Best view of the old barrels.< /Review>

< Review>
Great brewery environment and appreciate the eat on patio only rules. Easy to order as well using the QR code on the table.
Couple things that disappointed me:
1. The Brussel sprouts were seriously lacking in quantity (picture was after I had literally eaten just 2 pieces). For $8+ I expected more.
2. My wife is gluten allergic and specifically asked for her burger without buns thru their fancy online QR code ordering method but ended having to take the bun off herself. It's okay for her as she is only mildly allergic to wheat. But if you're more gluten allergic, I recommend ordering in person.

Other than those issues. Food was great (my spicy chicken sandwich was really good).<//Review>

0x80eeaba39ac328b9:0xecba7aa0c4f95cc2< /Gmap_id>
<Rating>5< /Rating>< Pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNPgG5HiiS53GkwfCJfaspwZ48iqQxxM2WSkkL2=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures>

< user_id>
112230048357302247725< /user_id>
<username>Lord Van Cannon< /username>< Date>
1602189740601< /Date>
< rate>
5< /rate>
< text>
If you can't make it to the primary location, come here.

Upon walking in I was greeted immediately. My party consisted of 7 people in total.

We chose the table next to the door. The restaurant was amazingly clean and the service was immediate.

First I will talk about the food and what we ordered. Then I'll speak about the brew. What we ordered is as follows. Calamari, French onion soup, fish tacos, taproom burger, basil chicken sandwich and last but not least the pretzel.

The calamari.
Not your traditional calamari. Asian infused with a honey glazed slaw. Is it bad by any means? No. It was tasty, but sweet. So be prepared for that.

French onion soup.
Just like my other review stands for their primary location. By far the best French onion soup I've ever had in California. Maybe even the states in general. That's saying A LOT! It's fresh. Perfectly caramelized onions, bread and broth soaked. With perfectly melted cheese. I HIGHLY recommend it!

Fish tacos.
Not your average fish tacos. But I have to be honest I didn't quite get to try them as much as I should. Because the table eat them so fast!

Taproom burger.
Not a frozen patty of any kind!
Loose meat patty seasoned perfectly. Asked to be cooked medium well.
It was absolutely perfect.
Raw onion, lettuce, tomato, avocado, bacon and I picked cheddar cheese.
The way a burger should be anywhere you go. THIS is a burger just like you'd take your time to make at home. To perfection.
HIGHLY recommend it.

Basil chicken sandwich.
Again I didn't get to try it as much as I'd like. It was eaten far to quickly. Which is a GOOD sign. My whole table was very picky eaters and everyone was satisfied.

Moving onto the brews.

I keep it simple usually with the Union Jack IPA.
But I did get a chance to try some sours.
Primarily "krieky bones"
I don't like sours much.  But this one is a must try.
As for the Union Jack? I'm sure many have written about that beer particularly all over online. As it's one of their most known beers ever made.

The atmosphere here on a early Sunday ( 11:45am ) was great.
Staff was amazing as was the cleanliness and presentation of the entire establishment.

With that said. I would highly recommend coming here. You won't be disappointed.

Food: Above
Decor: updates. No issues.
Staff/customer service: Excellent service. No complaints!
Cleanliness: Clean, no issues.
Bathroom: Clean. But only has air dryer for hands no towels.<//text>

< text>
Great destination for craft beer lovers and even the general public.  I've been here 3-4 times and each visit I'm amazed at how many barrel-aged wild ales and fortified stouts and blended strong ales they offer.  Barrelworks, by Firestone Walker, is the experimental version of their regular beer offerings and is next door to the regular brewery/brewpub.  Highly recommended if you enjoy bourbon-barrel aged Belgian quadruple ales, Russian Imperial Stouts and Wild Sour Ales.< /text>

<Rate>5</Rate>< Text>
This place is a nice little gem while driving through the middle of nowhere.  They serve some tasty appetizers and meals, and always have plenty of beers to choose from.
They actually have two different areas for different types of beers; the main brewery/ restaurant which serves the mainstream Firestone beers; and Barrelworks, which serves more of the craft and specialty beers.
This was my second time visiting Firestone Buelton, and I have to say I was impressed with the menu and service both times.<//Text>

< text>
Smaller than the other Firestone properties but this review focuses around the Barrelworks portion.  At this location they have a room that focuses on  barrel aged ales and sours.   At almost any point they will have a bunch of offers for you to try and often will have selections that are one off or from a specific barrel.  This can be neat to try the same beer but from different barrels.  I have also never seen the place very busy. I hear it is busy on release days but the times I have been are non-release and never busy.</text>

One of my top three favorite breweries! You MUST go to their Barrelworks tasting room if you want to sample their best beers! Strong ales and really good sour selections. The location is a bit out of the way, but the place is well worth the trip. Many top rated award winning beers to taste and take home. If you like craft beer you will love this brewery. < Review>
Very nice indeed ðŸ‘! My kind of style. From the exterior when you're parking and or walking up to open the entrance door for your special person or even for the very happy, fat, and I mean that in a good way, and forfilled patron and their party. It's a mix of both  rustic western and modern industrial architecture. Expect the same whenever you're inside with the obvious introduction of the well anticipated main attraction. The Ale! It's born right here inside this building. Take a deep breath and then relax. You know right away that you are not in the wrong place! I've seen all the beer flowing from the taps but that's not what overwhelms your senses,oh no, it's the food in the air. You know right then you're more hungry than you ever thought! Whether you're at the bar, in the lobby or sitting down in the dining room, either way, your experience is well worth any other choice you could have made in regards to where to go for a good place to eat , drink and enjoy your time with good people. Barrelworks, Firestone Brewery! Right here in our backyard in Buellton California. You won't regret this place for dinner. Put on your favorite boots and come hungry ! Before you go, don't be shy and purchase a few novelty items and or memorabilia to represent Firestone Brewery and remind yourself  where you have been.! Thank you and yes...there are food and beer Gods, JC.</Review>

<username>Randy Resnick</username><time>1504536125377<//time><rate>5< /rate><Review>Surprisingly good food and service. Even if you don't drink, you owe it to yourself to enjoy a meal at that surprising restaurant. We were a group of four, and we ordered 3 shareable starters, which was one too many, because when the main courses came, they were more than generous. The brisket of beef sandwich was delicious and the fries that came with it were crispy outside without being overcooked. One of us has a chicken salad, again, excellent. The Panko crumb breaded ahi tuna was a masterpiece. I never expected food to be this good in a brewery! It was early for drinking, or I would have tried the tasting flights they feature. We did have a glass of wine, and both were very good (at $9 they need to be good!).
Service: without exception, the service was great, whether in the tasting taproom or the restaurant. These folks are trained to be nice, but it seems to come natural to them. Kudos to the management of this place. Do not miss it if you are in the area!< /Review><Pictures>None</Pictures><Resp>None< /Resp><Gmap_id>0x80eeaba39ac328b9:0xecba7aa0c4f95cc2< /Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<user_name>Edward Heupler<//user_name>< Time>
1556249846288< /Time>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
If you love Firestone Walker brews (like I do) and you're in Santa Barbara County, then travel to Buellton (off Hwy 154) to tru this little gem. They make their wild ales here now, but the tasting room and restaurant are all Firestone Walker. The food (fish tacos for me, chopped salad for ther missus) were both delicious and well done. But it's the beers we came for, and they did NOT disappoint.
My wife sampled two stouts (both I'd had before) and loved them. I sampled five others, including a sour, a wild ale, a stout and two to-be-released IPAs inspired by "Game of Thrones". The Red IPA we bought as a crowler, but the Black was just as good.
Great service, helpful, knowledgeable staff who all enjoy working there: what's not to love?< /review>

<Text>I stopped in for their Barrelworks taproom.  It specializes in wild and other barrel aged strong/sour ales.  I've tasted a fair share of barrel aged beers in California, and these are of very high quality.  My only complaint is the price - $3 flat for all tasters is steep.  $15 for a 375mL is also steep.  Other breweries of equal quality are more affordable, but this is a common trend.  The taproom was nice and had a view of the storage warehouse.  Also,they seemed to cater to the wine crowd of the region, and it reflected in their silly flavor descriptions which didn't include the important information.</Text>< pics>

<review>Only 6 of the 12 or so taps open and nothing darker than a pale ale.  For a dark beer fan there was nothing to recommend. I was looking forward to a pint of stout or at least an amber, but if you didn't want a hoppy yellow beer your only other option was tiny shots of their barrelworks stuff.  Ordered the fish tacos.  Disgustingly tasteless. I ate one and tasted nothing but the salt and pepper I put on it half way through.  Left me a bit nauseous and sent away the other two.  No comment from the waitress. The quesadillas with chicken came  with no chicken (didn't get upcharged once we mentioned it). I was really underwhelmed and unlikely to return.  Maybe if I'd gone whole hog and ordered the steak and whatever IPA they were pushing I would have loved it, I don't know. I don't think places should just be judged on their most popular and expensive items.  If it's not good food, don't put it on the menu.

Just looked at pics of tacos on this review site!  Hah!  Not even close!  No seasoning on fish, no salsa, 1 lime wedge, about 1/10 the crema, no cilantro, the beans were mostly a brownish green watery mess with again about 1/10 the cheese pictured.< /review></record></dataset><record>

<Date>1473955016484<//Date>< rating>
4< /rating>
<Review>As to the brewery itself, if you like your 805 or other solid Firestone brews, then you know exactly what you're getting, except straight from the source. If you're like me, you enjoy a pleasant, knowledgeable and friendly conversational bar staff -- which is exactly what you're going to get here when you're ordering from their collection.

However, the true treat here comes in the form of Barrel Works, just in the back. Walk into the main dining area, nod and smile at all of the people, keep on walking, turn right and go into the funky room of exploration and wonderment.

That's right, you're in for a world of sour (beer)! If you've never tried sours or not had any beers crafted used wild strains of yeast, then you my friend, oh you're in for a treat. They have a rotating list of sours (10-15 depending) and strongs (7-10 depending) all of which are worth tasting. If you're in luck, you can get two of the same brews, just different releases, to try back-to-back.

When I was there last, I was lucky enough to get to try the Stickee Monkee from 2014 and the 2016. There is a difference and it's great to get them like that.

Now, if you want to take the unofficial challenge, do what I did, drink the entire list.

Probably not recommended unless you have a designated driver. If you do, then drink on my friend!

Oh, the pours are 3 oz. so you're going to be able to sample quite a few even if you don't have a friend driving you around on your tour, but be safe.

Now, have one for me!<//Review>< Pics>
None< /Pics>

<user_name>Pete Shieh< /user_name>< date>

<Text>I love Barrlworks. Their famous Bretta Weisse and Bretta Rose is excellent and like nothing I've ever tasted. Of course, you can't get this stuff unless you're here in their Buellton location. Most everything are in the barrels, just like what you see when you first walk in as you enter the taproom. It was nice and cool on a hot day walking through. That and a beer in your hand, makes this such a nice stop off the 101.  Tasters are $3 here.

I also recently tried one of their Feral series: Feral Vinifera Component: Orange Muscat. More on the sour side than on what I thought was sweet Muscat. Lovely to drink maybe as an aperitif or dessert., not something you will drink all the time.

So enough about their fu fu sours, if you also like their strong ales this place is a must. I got to try their Helldorado 2014 on tap. Strangely, the ABV on the 2015 is 1% higher. There is some agreesivenss in here, but it does make you want to drink more.  Definitely can taste the barrel taste.  Always a fan of their Parabola, Sticky Monkee, Sucaba.  Good stuff.

There's the fridge next to the tap which you can buy it to go. Of course, the older stuff like the Anniversary 14 or 15 is stupid expensive, I would totally just get the recent release and hope it ages fine at your own fridge.

I hope FW being bought won't change any of their beers, I love their beers and fan for life.< /Text><pictures>None<//pictures>< resp>
None<//resp>
